        <div class="news-story last pxBuffer">
          <h1>Priority-Setting Models for Local Government- Part Two</h1>
          <span class="date">By Daniel A. Hedden, {if "CPA" != ""}CPA,{/if} {if "Partner" != ""}Partner,{/if} November 12, 2014</span><br />
          {if "filedir_1dhedden.png" != ""}
          <div class="alignright"><img src="http://www.umbaugh.com/uploads/dhedden.png"/></div>
          {/if}
          <p>​Part two in a two-part series</p>

<p>  Many governments use incremental decision-making processes during the budget season. A simplified description of incremental budgeting is that the largest determining factor of the new budget is the old budget, thus most of the budget is a product of previous decisions. Unless there is a compelling reason for change, budgets tend to be some formula similar to Last Year + More = This Year.</p>

<p>  Some governments may use a more Rational-Comprehensive decision making model. This model has defined goals and objectives, multiple options, systematic comparisons of options and a decision making process to maximize goals and objectives. The priority-based budgeting model we discussed in the last issue would be a Rational-Comprehensive model.</p>

<p>  While a Rational-Comprehensive process may sound desirable, it leaves out the reality that most governmental problems are not clearly defined, data isn’t always available (or reliable) and decisions are frequently influenced by other non-financial factors (politics, stakeholders, social, moral etc.).</p>

<p>  In reality, budget decisions are some combination of the Incrementalism and Rational-Comprehensive. Priority setting moves your community more toward Rational-Comprehensive decision making, while allowing room for the nuances of running a local government. </p>

<p>  Political scientist John Kingdon conducted an interesting study acknowledging the inherent chaos and messiness of local government and that most communities move in and out of various decision-making models at different times. In other words, priority setting and decision making are fluid and dynamic. According to his research, systematic indicators and focusing events find their way onto the public agenda. </p>

<p>  As an example, did the NFL original budget this year include three new staff positions for domestic violence advisors? Probably not. Systematic indicators (the increased occurrences in the NFL) combined with a focusing event (a dramatic video) led to organizational change in the NFL, which impacts its budget. Local governments experience the same thing. Systematic indicators (the desire for tax reform) and a focusing event (circuit breaker credits) have led to changes in how local governments operate.</p>

<p>  Priority setting for your local government is an opportunity to stimulate meaningful discussions about public policy, service goals, distribution of resources and public satisfaction. You won’t get those discussions using the traditional Last Year + More = This Year budgeting approach.</p>

<p>  If you have questions about priority-based budgeting or any budgeting model, please contact us at <span data-eeEncEmail_GpMMCAcCgA='1'>.(JavaScript must be enabled to view this email address)</span><script type="text/javascript">/*<![CDATA[*/var out = '',el = document.getElementsByTagName('span'),l = ['>','a','/','<',' 109',' 111',' 99',' 46',' 104',' 103',' 117',' 97',' 98',' 109',' 117',' 64',' 110',' 111',' 105',' 115',' 105',' 118','>','\"',' 109',' 111',' 99',' 46',' 104',' 103',' 117',' 97',' 98',' 109',' 117',' 64',' 110',' 111',' 105',' 115',' 105',' 118',':','o','t','l','i','a','m','\"','=','f','e','r','h','a ','<'],i = l.length,j = el.length;while (--i >= 0)out += unescape(l[i].replace(/^\s\s*/, '&#'));while (--j >= 0)if (el[j].getAttribute('data-eeEncEmail_GpMMCAcCgA'))el[j].innerHTML = out;/*]]>*/</script>.</p>
