        <div class="news-story last pxBuffer">
          <h1>Priority-Setting Models for Local Government - Part One</h1>
          <span class="date">By Daniel A. Hedden, {if "CPA" != ""}CPA,{/if} {if "Partner" != ""}Partner,{/if} October 29, 2014</span><br />
          {if "filedir_1dhedden.png" != ""}
          <div class="alignright"><img src="http://www.umbaugh.com/uploads/dhedden.png"/></div>
          {/if}
          <p>​Part one in a series of two articles<br />
 <br />
 I recently read an interesting book called “Priority-Setting Models for Public Budgeting,” published by the Government Finance Officers Association. I’ve attended many meetings with local government officials over the years, and most budget discussions are devoted to how much to spend for people, supplies, outside services, debt and capital needs. While these items are important, I haven’t heard nearly as many discussions about what functions or programs are most important to a community. For example, if you had only $1,000 to spend, how would you allocate those dollars to the following typical governmental functions:</p><ol>
    <li>Public Safety</li>
    <li>Highways and Streets</li>
    <li>Economic Development</li>
    <li>Health and Welfare</li>
    <li>Redevelopment</li>
    <li>Sanitation</li>
    <li>Culture and Recreation</li>
    <li>General Government</li>
</ol>

<p>  Does your current budget match that distribution?</p>

<p>  If it doesn’t, consider whether priority-based budgeting may be valuable for your community.</p>

<p>  Priority setting is an objective process that articulates the functions and programs that are most important to your community. It helps determine what goods and services will be delivered to which persons at what cost. Priority setting helps communicate broad community goals into practical guidelines. This concept could lead to financial policies such as:</p>

<ol>
<li>Percentage of tax-supported subsidies versus direct user charges</li>
<li>Allocation of resources to each department</li>
<li>Determination of which services to continue, expand or eliminate</li>
<li>Setting operating balance reserves</li>
</ol>
<p>  We’ll put priority-based budgeting in a broader context in the second part of this series.<br />
 If you have questions about priority-based budgeting, please contact us at <span data-eeEncEmail_iIQhzxfskn='1'>.(JavaScript must be enabled to view this email address)</span><script type="text/javascript">/*<![CDATA[*/var out = '',el = document.getElementsByTagName('span'),l = ['>','a','/','<',' 109',' 111',' 99',' 46',' 104',' 103',' 117',' 97',' 98',' 109',' 117',' 64',' 110',' 111',' 105',' 115',' 105',' 118','>','\"',' 109',' 111',' 99',' 46',' 104',' 103',' 117',' 97',' 98',' 109',' 117',' 64',' 110',' 111',' 105',' 115',' 105',' 118',':','o','t','l','i','a','m','\"','=','f','e','r','h','a ','<'],i = l.length,j = el.length;while (--i >= 0)out += unescape(l[i].replace(/^\s\s*/, '&#'));while (--j >= 0)if (el[j].getAttribute('data-eeEncEmail_iIQhzxfskn'))el[j].innerHTML = out;/*]]>*/</script>.</p>
