        <div class="news-story last pxBuffer">
          <h1>How to Improve Internal Controls</h1>
          <span class="date">By Daniel A. Hedden, {if "CPA" != ""}CPA,{/if} {if "Partner" != ""}Partner,{/if} May 13, 2014</span><br />
          {if "filedir_1dhedden.png" != ""}
          <div class="alignright"><img src="http://www.umbaugh.com/uploads/dhedden.png"/></div>
          {/if}
          <p>Many units in Indiana have seen comments on recent State Board of Accounts reports citing a lack of internal controls. A common phrase in the audit is: “We found several instances where internal controls were deemed to be inadequate, which could impair the City’s ability to prevent and detect errors related to its recordkeeping.” Scary words, but what do they mean and what can your unit of government reasonably do to improve internal controls?</p>

<p> By definition, an internal control system is an integrated set of policies and procedures to assist management in achieving its goals and objectives. Typical goals are providing a favorable control environment, continually assessing risk, developing and maintaining effective control-based procedures and ongoing monitoring of policies’ and procedures’ effectiveness. The policies usually spell out how potential problems will be resolved. In short, management promotes an environment that prevents and detects inadvertent errors. <br />
 Examples of effective internal controls include:</p><ol>
    <li>Physical controls – Lock doors, lock safes, limit access, use passwords (other than 1234abcd), install (and actually use) alarm systems.</li>
    <li>Define responsibilities – This will help address questions if there is a breach in procedures. Defining duties protects the individual and your unit of government.</li>
    <li>Immediately document transactions – Generate a receipt, stamp received mail, create a register tape, review delivery slips, use pre-numbered invoices.</li>
    <li>Separate related duties – The person handling cash should not also reconcile the bank account, use separate cash registers with separate access, the person who orders goods should not also receive the goods and approve the payment of the invoice, the person ordering inventory should not be the same person who counts inventory.</li>
    <li>Supervisor review – Review the work of your internal resources and external consultants. If something does not make sense to management, seek an explanation.</li>
    <li>Internal audits – Periodically verify a task completed by a clerk for accuracy and reasonableness. Document your tests and findings.</li>
</ol>

<p> In a small governmental unit, assigning different people to related tasks and having different people in charge of an asset and the asset’s recordkeeping can go a long way to demonstrate internal controls. The Indiana State Board of Accounts will need to see documentation of your control environment. Written policies and procedures are helpful, but demonstrating that you adhere to those policies and procedures is better evidence of adequate internal controls. <br />
 In summary, internal control shortfalls are a common finding in recent audits. Implementing a corrective action plan may be easier than you think. Separate your related duties, supervise your internal and consulting work and document your findings.<br />
 If you have questions, please contact us at <span data-eeEncEmail_aCYAvzEbaX='1'>.(JavaScript must be enabled to view this email address)</span><script type="text/javascript">/*<![CDATA[*/var out = '',el = document.getElementsByTagName('span'),l = ['>','a','/','<',' 109',' 111',' 99',' 46',' 104',' 103',' 117',' 97',' 98',' 109',' 117',' 64',' 110',' 111',' 105',' 115',' 105',' 118','>','\"',' 109',' 111',' 99',' 46',' 104',' 103',' 117',' 97',' 98',' 109',' 117',' 64',' 110',' 111',' 105',' 115',' 105',' 118',':','o','t','l','i','a','m','\"','=','f','e','r','h','a ','<'],i = l.length,j = el.length;while (--i >= 0)out += unescape(l[i].replace(/^\s\s*/, '&#'));while (--j >= 0)if (el[j].getAttribute('data-eeEncEmail_aCYAvzEbaX'))el[j].innerHTML = out;/*]]>*/</script>.</p>
