        <div class="news-story last pxBuffer">
          <h1>Starke County Uses Creative Financing for Jail Expansion</h1>
          <span class="date">By Jason G. Semler, {if "CPA" != ""}CPA,{/if} {if "Principal" != ""}Principal,{/if} March 19, 2014</span><br />
          {if "filedir_1jsemler.png" != ""}
          <div class="alignright"><img src="http://www.umbaugh.com/uploads/jsemler.png"/></div>
          {/if}
          <p>Jail crowding could be on its way to your county – if it isn’t already there. A new law that goes into effect July 1 changes the A-D felony sentencing grid to a new six-level grid. The goal of this change to Indiana’s criminal code is to reserve state prisons for high-level offenders, while providing lower-level offenders with treatment-oriented rehabilitation at county jails and through community-based correction programs and probation. We have yet to see the effect on county jail capacity and living conditions. What we’ve seen in the past is that when jails become overcrowded, the potential for lawsuits certainly increases.</p>

<p> How do you fund jail expansion when local governments are already struggling to do more on less money?</p>

<p> Counties can put a referendum on the ballot to raise property taxes for jail expansion. But with school referendums running about a 50/50 success rate, you can imagine how difficult it is to persuade taxpayers to vote in favor of funding jails.</p>

<p> As an alternative to property taxes, Indiana counties can use existing income tax revenue streams or implement additional income tax rates to address both capital asset and operating needs for correctional facilities. Counties can also consider other existing local revenue sources (such as a cumulative jail fund), or funds on hand. In doing so, it is critical to take an in-depth look at the County’s overall financial position.</p>

<p> Starke County took a slightly different approach in 2012. With assistance from Umbaugh, Starke County adopted an additional County Economic Development Income Tax (CEDIT) rate of sixty-five hundredths of one percent (0.65%) imposed on the adjusted gross income of county taxpayers. Doing this required getting enabling legislation from the Indiana General Assembly. In Starke County’s case, the legislation allows the county to implement the rate to provide funding specific to its correctional facility and still maintain the low property tax rates they considered to be not only important to their constituents, but also essential to economic development.</p>

<p> Starke County issued bonds to fund a comprehensive project constructing new jail space and renovating its existing facility to address current needs and the needs for the foreseeable future. It also gave them the additional flexibility to address the impact of the new sentencing grid. Construction started in the fall of 2013 and will be completed in 2015. The additional CEDIT tax is designed to provide sufficient funding to repay the bonds and meet the ongoing operating expenses as needed.</p>

<p> As the impact of the new sentencing grid becomes more apparent throughout the state, more counties will need to expand their correctional facilities and services. Funding them through additional income tax is an option worth considering. Because this option requires local meetings to inform your constituents, legislative action, and time for construction, you need to plan ahead to get the process started. This planning process should not only include what the current and long-term needs are for the county’s correctional facility; but also a comprehensive evaluation of your current financial position/resources, as well as the funding alternatives.</p>

<p> If you have questions or need assistance with expanding local correctional facilities and services, please contact us at <span data-eeEncEmail_gWavyYGFya='1'>.(JavaScript must be enabled to view this email address)</span><script type="text/javascript">/*<![CDATA[*/var out = '',el = document.getElementsByTagName('span'),l = ['>','a','/','<',' 109',' 111',' 99',' 46',' 104',' 103',' 117',' 97',' 98',' 109',' 117',' 64',' 110',' 111',' 105',' 115',' 105',' 118','>','\"',' 109',' 111',' 99',' 46',' 104',' 103',' 117',' 97',' 98',' 109',' 117',' 64',' 110',' 111',' 105',' 115',' 105',' 118',':','o','t','l','i','a','m','\"','=','f','e','r','h','a ','<'],i = l.length,j = el.length;while (--i >= 0)out += unescape(l[i].replace(/^\s\s*/, '&#'));while (--j >= 0)if (el[j].getAttribute('data-eeEncEmail_gWavyYGFya'))el[j].innerHTML = out;/*]]>*/</script>.</p>
          <div id="tabs">
