        <div class="news-story last pxBuffer">
          <h1>SEC Delays New Rules For Municipal Advisors</h1>
          <span class="date">By Brian C. Colton, {if "CIPFA" != ""}CIPFA,{/if} {if "Partner" != ""}Partner,{/if} January 29, 2014</span><br />
          {if "filedir_1bcolton.png" != ""}
          <div class="alignright"><img src="http://www.umbaugh.com/uploads/bcolton.png"/></div>
          {/if}
          <p>It seems like a long time ago, but in July 2011 we explained in Footnotes that the Municipal Securities Rulemaking Board (MSRB) planned through its regulatory oversight to adopt a comprehensive set of rules for municipal advisors to prohibit fraudulent and manipulative practices and restrict conflicts of interest.</p>

<p>  Just before the new rules were set to go into effect January 13, 2014, the Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC) announced that full implementation will be delayed until July 1. </p>

<p>  It is a complex matter, and many participants still had questions.</p>

<p>  The new rules do not require a big change for Umbaugh because many of the requirements are consistent with how we already operate. We have always taken pride in our role as an independent financial advisor. We represent only our client’s side of a bond transaction, not the bond purchaser’s or investor’s. We make our clients’ long-term and financial interests our top priority.</p>

<p>  As the new July 1 deadline nears, we’ll explain more about what these rules mean in the bond marketplace. </p>

<p>  </p>

