        <div class="news-story last pxBuffer">
          <h1>Investing Your Core Balance for Greater Returns</h1>
          <span class="date">By Jeffrey A. Messer, {if "" != ""},{/if} {if "Director of Umbaugh Cash Advisory Services, LLC" != ""}Director of Umbaugh Cash Advisory Services, LLC,{/if} December 05, 2013</span><br />
          {if "filedir_1jmesser.png" != ""}
          <div class="alignright"><img src="http://www.umbaugh.com/uploads/jmesser.png"/></div>
          {/if}
          <p>We realize it’s hard to put active investing of your funds near the top of your to-do list when interest rates are near zero. However, with income budgets tight, every dollar you can earn from additional interest helps.</p>

<p>  We have written several times over the past few years about the importance of using a structured approach for investing public funds. By structured we mean investing in longer maturities and using all the tools available in Indiana Code for public fund investments. You can earn additional interest by investing just a bit further out on the yield curve in a consistent manner.</p>

<p>  To determine whether it’s worth doing more than just using a sweep account or rolling short-term CDs, look at your total cash balances to see if you have a “core” investable balance. One easy way to find your core balance is to review your fund balance reports for the last two or three years (for cities and towns, use utility balances as well) to see what the lowest monthly total bank balance was over that period. The lowest monthly balance is your starting point for determining your core balance. If you have $5 million or more, it may be worthwhile to consider the next step for creating your investment program.</p>

<p>  As always, investment of public funds should focus on safety, liquidity and return, in that order. Our next Footnotes will explain how to put your core balance to work and how you can use provisions of Indiana Code to help.</p>

<p>  </p>

<p>  If you have questions or need help with your investment processes and options, please contact us at <span data-eeEncEmail_mGkovuMOxj='1'>.(JavaScript must be enabled to view this email address)</span><script type="text/javascript">/*<![CDATA[*/var out = '',el = document.getElementsByTagName('span'),l = ['>','a','/','<',' 109',' 111',' 99',' 46',' 104',' 103',' 117',' 97',' 98',' 109',' 117',' 64',' 110',' 111',' 105',' 115',' 105',' 118','>','\"',' 109',' 111',' 99',' 46',' 104',' 103',' 117',' 97',' 98',' 109',' 117',' 64',' 110',' 111',' 105',' 115',' 105',' 118',':','o','t','l','i','a','m','\"','=','f','e','r','h','a ','<'],i = l.length,j = el.length;while (--i >= 0)out += unescape(l[i].replace(/^\s\s*/, '&#'));while (--j >= 0)if (el[j].getAttribute('data-eeEncEmail_mGkovuMOxj'))el[j].innerHTML = out;/*]]>*/</script>.</p>
