        <div class="news-story last pxBuffer">
          <h1>Strategic Budgeting for Local Governments: It&#8217;s Always Budget Season Part 3</h1>
          <span class="date">By Daniel A. Hedden, {if "CPA" != ""}CPA,{/if} {if "Partner" != ""}Partner,{/if} November 20, 2013</span><br />
          {if "filedir_1dhedden.png" != ""}
          <div class="alignright"><img src="http://www.umbaugh.com/uploads/dhedden.png"/></div>
          {/if}
          <p>Previous articles in this series have stressed the importance of creating long-term goals that drive your budgeting process. You begin with discussions to assess community needs, priorities and challenges and to identify opportunities and challenges for government services, capital assets and management. The next step is to develop broad goals to provide overall direction and serve as a basis for decision making. Setting broad goals isn’t the end product, because you will never reach your goals unless you develop approaches to achieve them. Those approaches include:</p><ul>
    <li>Adopting financial policies</li>
    <li>Developing programmatic, operating and capital policies and plans</li>
    <li>Developing programs and services consistent with the policies and plans</li>
    <li>Developing management strategies </li>
</ul>

<p>  What might those policies, plans and strategies look like? Here’s a sample of what you might consider including:</p><ul>
    <li>We will maintain a operating balance in all funds that support core operations (general fund, parks, etc.) for at least two months</li>
    <li>We will establish a unit cost and useful life for all capital assets, and then use that information in our budgeting process.</li>
    <li>Trash services will be cost based.</li>
    <li>Culture and recreation services will recover x% of their costs through direct fees.</li>
    <li>Employees will share in x% of insurance costs.</li>
    <li>Staffing levels will be based on an industry standard (then specify which industry standard you will use).</li>
    <li>Vehicles will be replaced based on the pre-determined conditions (such as mileage, hours of operation or years of service).</li>
    <li>We will organize quarterly meetings for budget management.</li>
    <li>The Rainy Day Fund will be used under these conditions:</li>
    <li>Budget surplus will be handled as follows: </li>
</ul>

<p>  Once you have policies, plans and strategies that fit your situation, it is much easier to make decisions and measure performance. And that’s what we’ll cover in our next article: How to evaluate performance and make adjustments. <i></i></p>

<p><i> </i><i>If you have questions or need help with budgets, long-term goals or projecting year-end cash balances, please contact us at <span data-eeEncEmail_ERRUaLiaSp='1'>.(JavaScript must be enabled to view this email address)</span><script type="text/javascript">/*<![CDATA[*/var out = '',el = document.getElementsByTagName('span'),l = ['>','a','/','<',' 109',' 111',' 99',' 46',' 104',' 103',' 117',' 97',' 98',' 109',' 117',' 64',' 110',' 111',' 105',' 115',' 105',' 118','>','\"',' 109',' 111',' 99',' 46',' 104',' 103',' 117',' 97',' 98',' 109',' 117',' 64',' 110',' 111',' 105',' 115',' 105',' 118',':','o','t','l','i','a','m','\"','=','f','e','r','h','a ','<'],i = l.length,j = el.length;while (--i >= 0)out += unescape(l[i].replace(/^\s\s*/, '&#'));while (--j >= 0)if (el[j].getAttribute('data-eeEncEmail_ERRUaLiaSp'))el[j].innerHTML = out;/*]]>*/</script>.</i></p>
          <div id="tabs">
            <ul>
              <li id="first"><a href="#tabs-1">Give Article Feedback</a> &raquo;</li>
              <li>|</li>
              <li><a href="#tabs-2">E-mail Umbaugh</a> &raquo;</li>
              <li>|</li>
              <li>
                <FORM>
                  <INPUT TYPE="button" value="Print Article" onClick="window.print()" class="articleBtn">
                </FORM>
              </li>
