        <div class="news-story last pxBuffer">
          <h1>BULLETIN – TIF UPDATE</h1>
          <span class="date">By Umbaugh Announcements, {if "" != ""},{/if} {if "" != ""},{/if} November 13, 2013</span><br />
          {if "" != ""}
          <div class="alignright"><img src=""/></div>
          {/if}
          <p>ANALYZE THE CONSEQUENCES OF KEEPING RESIDENTIAL PROPERTIES IN YOUR TIF ALLOCATION AREA</p>

<p> On October 18, 2013 the Department of Local Government Finance (DLGF) circulated a memo to all county Auditors and tax and billing software vendors regarding how the base assessed value for tax increment financing (TIF) is calculated.  In this memo, the DLGF affirmed its interpretation of Indiana code that the base assessed value of an allocation area consists of all property, &lt;span style=&#8220;text-decoration: underline;&#8221;&gt;including residential property&lt;/span&gt;. This interpretation is being used in the current round of software testing and may have a direct impact on calculating incremental assessed value in TIF allocation areas going forward.</p>

<p> To summarize the key points of the memo:</p><ul>
    <li>increases in assessed value to residential parcels may not be added to the assessed value that is captured in a TIF allocation area, but</li>
    <li>decreases in assessed value to residential parcels may decrease the amount of assessed value that is captured in a TIF allocation area, thus decreasing TIF revenues you receive.</li>
</ul>

<p> <br />
 Please note this impacts only TIF allocation areas in which residential parcels are not eligible to be captured. Given this affirmed interpretation from the DLGF, we recommend you consider the effects of a) continuing to include residential parcels in existing TIF allocation areas if residential parcels may not be captured and b) including residential parcels when considering creating a new TIF allocation area.</p>

<p> Your county Auditor&#8217;s office should be able to generate reports for your TIF allocation areas that identify the property type for each parcel.  Use these reports to determine the amount of residential net assessed value within each of your TIF allocation areas. Once you review the residential parcels in your TIF Area, you can make an informed decision either to leave the boundaries of your TIF Allocation Area alone and keep the residential parcels or to amend your TIF Allocation Area to remove the residential parcels.</p>

<p> <i>We at Umbaugh are pleased to assist you in your analysis of TIF allocation areas and the possible impact of residential parcels on TIF assessed values. If you have questions or need assistance, please contact us at <span data-eeEncEmail_XlHKjKbnox='1'>.(JavaScript must be enabled to view this email address)</span><script type="text/javascript">/*<![CDATA[*/var out = '',el = document.getElementsByTagName('span'),l = ['>','a','/','<',' 109',' 111',' 99',' 46',' 104',' 103',' 117',' 97',' 98',' 109',' 117',' 64',' 110',' 111',' 105',' 115',' 105',' 118','>','\"',' 109',' 111',' 99',' 46',' 104',' 103',' 117',' 97',' 98',' 109',' 117',' 64',' 110',' 111',' 105',' 115',' 105',' 118',':','o','t','l','i','a','m','\"','=','f','e','r','h','a ','<'],i = l.length,j = el.length;while (--i >= 0)out += unescape(l[i].replace(/^\s\s*/, '&#'));while (--j >= 0)if (el[j].getAttribute('data-eeEncEmail_XlHKjKbnox'))el[j].innerHTML = out;/*]]>*/</script>.</i></p>
