        <div class="news-story last pxBuffer">
          <h1>Arbitrage Rebate – Are You in Compliance?</h1>
          <span class="date">By Doug L. Baldessari, {if "CPA" != ""}CPA,{/if} {if "Partner" != ""}Partner,{/if} November 02, 2013</span><br />
          {if "filedir_1dbaldessari.png" != ""}
          <div class="alignright"><img src="http://www.umbaugh.com/uploads/dbaldessari.png"/></div>
          {/if}
          <p>Does your city or town issue tax-exempt municipal bonds?  If so, arbitrage rules apply.</p>

<p> Arbitrage refers to investment earnings on tax-exempt bond proceeds in excess of what is allowed by the rules, resulting in profit.  If you earn a profit, you have to pay it back to the federal government.  It is the responsibility of the local unit issuing the bonds to determine what amount, if any, is owed.  If arbitrage payments are required, they are due beginning five years after the bonds were issued.  There are certain exceptions which may apply, such as the small issuer and spend down, but the rules are complex and you will probably need assistance to determine which exceptions apply to each bond issue. </p>

<p> Recent municipal bonds were issued at historically low bond interest rates.  Do you have a compliance plan to deal with rising investment rates? </p>

<p> What if the small-issuer exception is met, but bond proceeds that were not spent within the construction period are left in the construction account?  Arbitrage payments to the federal government may be due in certain circumstances.</p>

<p> If you owe arbitrage payments to the federal government, is that a bad thing?  Not necessarily, because it means you earned the maximum amount of investment earnings allowed on your bond proceeds. You do, however, need to budget for the arbitrage payments from the investment earnings.</p>

<p> We have seen more audits of municipal bond issues lately. Post-issuance tax compliance appears to be a priority for the IRS, as we have seen an increasing number of IRS questionnaires and audits in recent years regarding tax-exempt bond issues.  </p>

<p> For all these reasons you need an arbitrage compliance plan and periodic calculations.  This will help ensure you are in compliance and that you budget for any arbitrage payments that may be due.</p>

<p>  </p>

<p> If you need assistance or have questions, please contact us at <span data-eeEncEmail_TFwspQKuLH='1'>.(JavaScript must be enabled to view this email address)</span><script type="text/javascript">/*<![CDATA[*/var out = '',el = document.getElementsByTagName('span'),l = ['>','a','/','<',' 109',' 111',' 99',' 46',' 104',' 103',' 117',' 97',' 98',' 109',' 117',' 64',' 110',' 111',' 105',' 115',' 105',' 118','>','\"',' 109',' 111',' 99',' 46',' 104',' 103',' 117',' 97',' 98',' 109',' 117',' 64',' 110',' 111',' 105',' 115',' 105',' 118',':','o','t','l','i','a','m','\"','=','f','e','r','h','a ','<'],i = l.length,j = el.length;while (--i >= 0)out += unescape(l[i].replace(/^\s\s*/, '&#'));while (--j >= 0)if (el[j].getAttribute('data-eeEncEmail_TFwspQKuLH'))el[j].innerHTML = out;/*]]>*/</script>.</p>
